content:
The `TabBar` component provides a user interface for managing a collection of tabs, allowing users to switch between them, close them, and open new ones.

## Purpose

This component is designed to be a flexible and interactive tab navigation system. It visually represents a set of tabs, highlights the currently active tab, and provides controls for user interaction.

## Key Exports

### `TabBar` Component

This is the main component exported by the file. It takes several props to configure its behavior and appearance.

#### Props

*   `tabs`: An array of `Tab` objects. Each `Tab` object should have at least an `id` (string) and a `label` (string).
    ```typescript
    interface Tab {
      id: string;
      label: string;
      // ... other potential properties
    }
    ```
*   `activeTabId`: A string representing the ID of the currently active tab. This prop is used to visually distinguish the active tab.
*   `onSwitch`: A callback function that is invoked when a user clicks on a tab to switch to it. It receives the `id` of the clicked tab as an argument.
*   `onClose`: A callback function that is invoked when a user clicks the close button on a tab. It receives the `id` of the tab to be closed as an argument. This function is only called if there is more than one tab open.
*   `onAdd`: A callback function that is invoked when the "New tab" button is clicked. This is typically used to trigger the creation of a new tab.

## Usage Example

```tsx
import React, { useState } from 'react';
import { TabBar } from './TabBar'; // Assuming TabBar is in the same directory
import type { Tab } from './types';

const App: React.FC = () => {
  const [tabs, setTabs] = useState<Tab[]>([
    { id: 'tab1', label: 'Tab 1' },
    { id: 'tab2', label: 'Tab 2' },
  ]);
  const [activeTabId, setActiveTabId] = useState<string>('tab1');
  const [nextTabId, setNextTabId] = useState<number>(3);

  const handleSwitchTab = (id: string) => {
    setActiveTabId(id);
  };

  const handleCloseTab = (id: string) => {
    setTabs(tabs.filter(tab => tab.id !== id));
    // If the closed tab was active, switch to another tab
    if (activeTabId === id && tabs.length > 1) {
      setActiveTabId(tabs.find(tab => tab.id !== id)?.id || '');
    }
  };

  const handleAddTab = () => {
    const newTabId = `tab${nextTabId}`;
    setTabs([...tabs, { id: newTabId, label: `Tab ${nextTabId}` }]);
    setNextTabId(prev => prev + 1);
    setActiveTabId(newTabId); // Make the new tab active
  };

  return (
    <div>
      <TabBar
        tabs={tabs}
        activeTabId={activeTabId}
        onSwitch={handleSwitchTab}
        onClose={handleCloseTab}
        onAdd={handleAddTab}
      />
      {/* Content for the active tab would go here */}
      <div>Content for {tabs.find(tab => tab.id === activeTabId)?.label}</div>
    </div>
  );
};

export default App;
```

## Styling

The component relies on CSS classes for styling. Common classes include `tab-bar`, `tab-list`, `tab`, `active`, `tab-label`, `tab-close`, and `tab-add`. You will need to provide the corresponding CSS rules to style the tab bar as desired.
